# {{.Name}} ({{.Type}})

Manages an EKS cluster registered with CloudPilot AI. This resource handles the full lifecycle: installing the CloudPilot AI agent, configuring rebalance settings, and managing node pools and node classes.

~> **Note:** Provider-side `workload_templates`, `nodeclass_templates`, `nodepool_templates`, and per-object `template_name` fields are deprecated. For reusable template composition, prefer the [`cloudpilot-ai/eks/cloudpilotai`](https://registry.terraform.io/modules/cloudpilot-ai/eks/cloudpilotai/latest) module, which renders shared config before it reaches the provider.

## Example Usage

{{ tffile "examples/resources/cloudpilotai_eks_cluster/resource.tf" }}

### AWS/EKS Node Config Fields

```terraform
cluster_setting = {
  enable_node_repair  = true
  enable_disk_monitor = true
  discount            = 0.15
  pre_run_command = <<-EOT
    set -euo pipefail

    echo "pre run start"
    aws sts get-caller-identity
    kubectl get nodes
  EOT
  post_run_command = <<-EOT
    set -euo pipefail

    echo "post run start"
    kubectl get pods -A
  EOT
}

nodeclasses = [
  {
    name      = "cloudpilot"
    ami_alias = "al2023@latest"
    user_data = "#!/bin/bash\necho cloudpilot"
    block_device_mappings = [
      {
        device_name = "/dev/xvda"
        root_volume = true
        ebs = {
          volume_size = "80Gi"
          volume_type = "gp3"
          encrypted   = true
        }
      }
    ]
  }
]

nodepools = [
  {
    name   = "cloudpilot-general"
    labels = { team = "platform" }
    taints = [{ key = "dedicated", value = "wa", effect = "NoSchedule" }]
  }
]
```

~> **Note:** `cluster_setting.pre_run_command` and `cluster_setting.post_run_command` are still stored in the CloudPilot service so the frontend can surface them for manual script copying.

When the Terraform provider runs cluster-scoped rebalance or upgrade scripts itself, it overrides conflicting `AWS_PROFILE`, temporary AWS credential environment variables, `CUSTOM_NODE_ROLE`, and `aws ... --profile ...` fragments before local execution by using the AWS credentials derived from provider-level `aws_profile` and `aws_assume_role`, along with `custom_node_role`.

{{ .SchemaMarkdown | trimspace }}

## Import

Import only requires a valid CloudPilot AI API key — no AWS credentials, profile, or kubeconfig needed. All configuration is fetched from the CloudPilot AI API.

{{ codefile "shell" "examples/resources/cloudpilotai_eks_cluster/import.sh" }}

After importing, the resource state will contain the cluster's full configuration including rebalance settings, workloads, node classes, and node pools fetched from the server. You can then manage them via `terraform apply`.

~> **Note:** To perform create, update, or delete operations after import, you will need to add `aws_profile`, `aws_assume_role`, and/or `kubeconfig` to your configuration so CloudPilot can reach the real AWS cluster.
